I could be wrong, of course. There are risks. It'll take time for all of this to play out. But I remain optimistic that Netflix will be a winner over the next 10 years, just as it has over the past 10 and 20 years.

Netflix isn't going anywhere. Revenue is growing, profitability is rising, the business is scaling, and most (all?) of the incoming competition is slow and following (not disrupting) Netflix. And Netflix is lead by one of the most capable, proven management teams of the century.

Let's not forget this is the same biz that's lead three major business model innovations: 

1) DVDs by mail
1b) dismantling Blockbuster
2) online streaming
3) original content 

Now that Disney is entering the streaming game, you really think Netflix is gonna roll over? Heck no.

Netflix has a huge headstart on every other media company from a user data and content production perspective. This can't be replicated overnight. By the time it is replicated (likely years from now), I have confidence Reed Hastings and co will have innovated far beyond.

Disney is a great company (I own shares) but it is slow. It's taken Disney *12 years* to launch its streaming service after Netflix announced its streaming site in January 2007. How long will it take Disney to follow in Netflix's footsteps next time?

Disney+ is continually seen as a dark cloud hanging over Netflix's head. Disney+ will do well, but it'll take YEARS for Disney+ to reach the scale that Netflix has TODAY. Disney+ won't reach 100M+ subscribers for several years. In the meantime, Netflix will continue leading.
